title: Strict_inequality

# Strict inequality (!==)

 The **strict inequality (`!==`)** operator checks whether its two operands are not equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the [inequality](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Inequality) operator, the strict inequality operator always considers operands of different types to be different.

## [Try it](#try%5Fit)

## [Syntax](#syntax)

```
x !== y

```

## [Description](#description)

 The strict inequality operator checks whether its operands are not equal. It is the negation of the[strict equality](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Strict%5Fequality) operator so the following two lines will always give the same result:

```
x !== y;

!(x === y);

```

 For details of the comparison algorithm, see the page for the[strict equality](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Strict%5Fequality) operator.

 Like the strict equality operator, the strict inequality operator will always consider operands of different types to be different:

```
3 !== "3"; // true

```

## [Examples](#examples)

### [Comparing operands of the same type](#comparing%5Foperands%5Fof%5Fthe%5Fsame%5Ftype)

```
"hello" !== "hello"; // false
"hello" !== "hola"; // true

3 !== 3; // false
3 !== 4; // true

true !== true; // false
true !== false; // true

null !== null; // false

```

### [Comparing operands of different types](#comparing%5Foperands%5Fof%5Fdifferent%5Ftypes)

```
"3" !== 3; // true
true !== 1; // true
null !== undefined; // true

```

### [Comparing objects](#comparing%5Fobjects)

```
const object1 = {
  key: "value",
};

const object2 = {
  key: "value",
};

console.log(object1 !== object2); // true
console.log(object1 !== object1); // false

```
